<dd>(<span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22">Google</a> (<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22+-wikipedia">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22+site:news.google.com/newspapers&amp;source=newspapers">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/search?safe=off&amp;tbs=sur:fmc&amp;tbm=isch&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22+-site:wikipedia.org+-site:wikimedia.org">free images</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/custom?hl=en&amp;cx=007734830908295939403%3Agalkqgoksq0&amp;cof=FORID%3A13%3BAH%3Aleft%3BCX%3AWikipedia%2520Reference%2520Search&amp;q=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22">WP refs</a>)&#160;<b>·</b> <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Free_English_newspaper_sources">FENS</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.nytimes.com/search/%22Congregation+of+the+Heart+of+Mary%22">NYT</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://wikipedialibrary.wmflabs.org/partners/">TWL</a></span>)</dd></dl>
<p>There is no such thing as "Congregation of the Heart of Mary". This page simply lists unrelated <a href="/wiki/Religious_congregation" title="Religious congregation">religious congregations</a> whose names happen to contain "Heart of Mary". Neither a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Broad-concept_article" title="Wikipedia:Broad-concept article">broad concept article</a> or a disambiguation page is suitable (because none of those listed here is actually called "Congregation of the Heart of Mary"). This might have been a useful page in the 1913 <i>Catholic Encyclopedia</i>, where it was copied from, but Wikipedia does not lump unrelated things together like this. <span style="font-family: serif; letter-spacing: 0.1em">–&#160;<a href="/wiki/User:Finnusertop" title="User:Finnusertop">Finnusertop</a></span> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Finnusertop" title="User talk:Finnusertop">talk</a> ⋅ <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Finnusertop" title="Special:Contributions/Finnusertop">contribs</a>) 11:33, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p><p><b>Withdrawn by nominator</b> see the reply below. <span style="font-family: serif; letter-spacing: 0.1em">–&#160;<a href="/wiki/User:Finnusertop" title="User:Finnusertop">Finnusertop</a></span> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Finnusertop" title="User talk:Finnusertop">talk</a> ⋅ <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Finnusertop" title="Special:Contributions/Finnusertop">contribs</a>) 20:49, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Christianity" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Christianity">list of Christianity-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Shellwood" title="User:Shellwood">Shellwood</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shellwood" title="User talk:Shellwood">talk</a>) 12:32, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd>
<dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Disambiguations" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Disambiguations">list of Disambiguations-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:MarginalCost&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:MarginalCost (page does not exist)">MarginalCost</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:MarginalCost" title="User talk:MarginalCost">talk</a>) 14:37, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Comment</b> - the nom is essentially correct in saying that this article does not describe a single entity or concept, and thus should effectively be treated as a disambiguation page, with the relevant policy essentially coming down to something like <a href="/wiki/MOS:DABMENTION" class="mw-redirect" title="MOS:DABMENTION">MOS:DABMENTION</a>. I note that one of the linked groups, <a href="/wiki/CICM_Missionaries" title="CICM Missionaries">CICM Missionaries</a> is known as "Congregation of the <u>Immaculate</u> Heart of Mary." How important is the distinction? Is the phrase overly general such that a redirect would be inappropriate? I'm not certain and will wait for others to weigh in. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:MarginalCost&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:MarginalCost (page does not exist)">MarginalCost</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:MarginalCost" title="User talk:MarginalCost">talk</a>) 14:52, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li>'<b>Keep</b>, or failing that, split into an article/stub for each of the separate orders so as not to lose content. But I think the reader is probably better served by this long-standing multi-topic article. If gathering them under the title "Congregations of the Heart of Mary" seemed appropriate to the editors of the Catholic encyclopedia, experts in the subject area (I'm not), we're probably best to continue with it. (Our title was plural until a recent page move). <a href="/wiki/User:PamD" title="User:PamD"><span style="color: green"><i><b>Pam</b></i></span></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:PamD" title="User talk:PamD"><span style="color: brown"><i><b>D</b></i></span></a> 16:08, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Keep</b>. This looks to me like a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Set_index_article" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Set index article">Wikipedia:Set index article</a>: <span class="example" style="font-family: Georgia, &#39;DejaVu Serif&#39;, serif; color: #006400;">a list article about a set of items of a specific type</span> (Roman Catholic religious Congregations) <span class="example" style="font-family: Georgia, &#39;DejaVu Serif&#39;, serif; color: #006400;">that also share the same (or similar) name</span> ("Heart of Mary"). The plural title might well have been better. <a href="/wiki/User:Shhhnotsoloud" title="User:Shhhnotsoloud">Shhhnotsoloud</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shhhnotsoloud" title="User talk:Shhhnotsoloud">talk</a>) 16:51, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
<ul><li>Actually, I think you're right, <a href="/wiki/User:Shhhnotsoloud" title="User:Shhhnotsoloud">Shhhnotsoloud</a>. It being a SIA didn't occur to me. <b>Withdrawn</b>. <span style="font-family: serif; letter-spacing: 0.1em">–&#160;<a href="/wiki/User:Finnusertop" title="User:Finnusertop">Finnusertop</a></span> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Finnusertop" title="User talk:Finnusertop">talk</a> ⋅ <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Finnusertop" title="Special:Contributions/Finnusertop">contribs</a>) 20:49, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li></ul>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Jamal_Azzam"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Jamal_Azzam&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Jamal Azzam (page does not exist)">Jamal Azzam</a></span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Jamal_Azzam&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-1" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>

<p>Would have sent it back to draft, but there really doesn't seem to be any point. <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BIO1E" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BIO1E">WP:BIO1E</a> would seem to apply here, fails <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NSOLDIER" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NSOLDIER">WP:NSOLDIER</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Onel5969" title="User:Onel5969"><b><span style="color:#536895;">Onel</span><span style="color:#ffb300;">5969</span></b></a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Onel5969" title="User talk:Onel5969"><i style="color:blue">TT me</i></a></sup> 11:26, 12 August 2019 (UTC)

<ul><li><b>Delete</b> BLP1E applies; GNG and NSOLDIER are not met. This has been draftified twice and made its way back to article space without significant improvements that may show notability . AfD was the right course of action. <sub>pseudonym</sub> <a href="/wiki/User:Jake_Brockman" title="User:Jake Brockman">Jake Brockman</a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jake_Brockman" title="User talk:Jake Brockman">talk</a></sup> 13:32, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b> Fails <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NSOLDIER" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NSOLDIER">WP:NSOLDIER</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BIO1E" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BIO1E">WP:BIO1E</a> applies here.<a href="/wiki/User:Pharaoh_of_the_Wizards" title="User:Pharaoh of the Wizards">Pharaoh of the Wizards</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Pharaoh_of_the_Wizards" title="User talk:Pharaoh of the Wizards">talk</a>) 06:27, 18 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<dl><dd><span id="Asurankundu_Dam"></span><span class="plainlinks nourlexpansion lx"><a href="/wiki/Asurankundu_Dam" title="Asurankundu Dam">Asurankundu Dam</a> (<a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;action=edit">edit</a>&#160;&#124; <a href="/wiki/Talk:Asurankundu_Dam" title="Talk:Asurankundu Dam">talk</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;action=history">history</a><span class="sysop-show">&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;action=protect">protect</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;action=delete">delete</a></span>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere/Asurankundu_Dam&amp;limit=999">links</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;action=watch">watch</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Log&amp;page=Asurankundu+Dam">logs</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="//tools.wmflabs.org/pageviews?pages=Asurankundu_Dam&amp;project=en.wikipedia.org">views</a>)</span> – (<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Asurankundu_Dam" title="Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Asurankundu Dam">View AfD</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <span class="plainlinks"><a class="external text" href="https://tools.wmflabs.org/jackbot/snottywong/cgi-bin/votecounter.cgi?page=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Asurankundu_Dam">Stats</a></span>)</dd>

<p>Minor geographical feature failing <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GEOFEAT" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GEOFEAT">WP:GEOFEAT</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User:Curb Safe Charmer">Curb Safe Charmer</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User talk:Curb Safe Charmer">talk</a>) 10:25, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Geography" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Geography">list of Geography-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User:Curb Safe Charmer">Curb Safe Charmer</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User talk:Curb Safe Charmer">talk</a>) 10:25, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd>
<dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/India" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/India">list of India-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User:Curb Safe Charmer">Curb Safe Charmer</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Curb_Safe_Charmer" title="User talk:Curb Safe Charmer">talk</a>) 10:25, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Keep</b> The dam and associated reservoir are clearly a significant geographic feature in the landscape. It is similar in size to <a href="/wiki/Toddbrook_Reservoir" title="Toddbrook Reservoir">Toddbrook Reservoir</a>, and we shouldn't forgo an article on it simply because sources are harder to come by, per <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WORLDVIEW" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:WORLDVIEW">WP:WORLDVIEW</a>.----<a href="/wiki/User:Pontificalibus" title="User:Pontificalibus"><strong style="color:#555555">Pontificalibus</strong></a> 10:24, 14 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Keep</b>. It is a combo article about a dam and reservoir and forest and recreation area, and as noted in the article it can potentially become a bigger tourist attraction. See really excellent essay <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION">wp:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION</a>. Could/should be developed more about the latter aspects, and perhaps eventually moved to a broader title such as "Asurankundu Dam and Recreation Area" or whatever term properly describes it in larger terms. As Pontificalibus notes, just covering the dam and reservoir suffices already. --<a href="/wiki/User:Doncram" title="User:Doncram">Doncram</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doncram" title="User talk:Doncram">talk</a>) 20:25, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Keep</b> passes <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GEOFEAT" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GEOFEAT">WP:GEOFEAT</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION">WP:ITSATOURISTATTRACTION</a>. --<b> <a href="/wiki/User:Harshil169" title="User:Harshil169"><i style="color:orange; font-family:Brush Script MT">Harshil </i></a></b><sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Harshil169" title="User talk:Harshil169">want to talk?</a></sup> 04:28, 17 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<p><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BLP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BLP">WP:BLP</a> of a person notable only as a former member of a county government. This is not a level of political office that gets an automatic free pass over <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NPOL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NPOL">WP:NPOL</a> -- but the references here are 50 per cent <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:PRIMARYSOURCES" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:PRIMARYSOURCES">primary sources</a> that are not support for notability at all, and 50 per cent deadlinked routine local coverage in a smalltown community hyperlocal. This is not a sufficient depth, range or volume of coverage to make a county councillor notable. <a href="/wiki/User:Bearcat" title="User:Bearcat">Bearcat</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bearcat" title="User talk:Bearcat">talk</a>) 07:44, 5 August 2019 (UTC)

<ul><li><b>Delete</b> Clear <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NPOL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NPOL">WP:NPOL</a> fail. Best, <a href="/wiki/User:GPL93" title="User:GPL93">GPL93</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:GPL93" title="User talk:GPL93">talk</a>) 11:57, 5 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b> We really need to do better at cleaning out these articles on non-notable local level politicians.<a href="/wiki/User:Johnpacklambert" title="User:Johnpacklambert">John Pack Lambert</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Johnpacklambert" title="User talk:Johnpacklambert">talk</a>) 05:58, 6 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Comments</b> - I'm torn here. <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:POLOUTCOMES" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:POLOUTCOMES">Normally</a>, articles about a county official are deleted, but this might be a special case. He did garner <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:SIGCOV" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:SIGCOV">ongoing coverage in reliable sources</a>. I recall this scandal; it was big news in <a href="/wiki/Upstate_New_York" title="Upstate New York">Upstate New York</a>. The community would have to decide if that's enough. <a href="/wiki/User:Bearian" title="User:Bearian">Bearian</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bearian" title="User talk:Bearian">talk</a>) 21:18, 6 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<div class="xfd_relist" style="border-top: 1px solid #AAA; border-bottom: 1px solid #AAA; padding: 0px 25px;"><span style="color: #FF6600;"><b><span style="font-size:91%;"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Deletion_process#Relisting_discussions" title="Wikipedia:Deletion process">Relisted</a> to generate a more thorough discussion and clearer consensus.</span></b></span><br />
<small>Please add new comments below this notice. Thanks, <a href="/wiki/User:Yunshui" title="User:Yunshui">Yunshui</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Yunshui" title="User talk:Yunshui"><sup style="font-size:90%">雲</sup></a><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Yunshui" title="Special:Contributions/Yunshui"><sub style="font-size:90%">水</sub></a> 09:57, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></div>
<ul><li><b>Keep</b>, non notable politician who fails NPOL yet passes <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a>. Subject became notable by being disbarred in 2005 for malfeasance, and a felony arrest and conviction 2012 for practicing as a disbarred lawyer, and denial of appeal in 2016. I added several sources including New York State Court of appeals and Buffalo news. <a href="/wiki/User:Lightburst" title="User:Lightburst">Lightburst</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Lightburst" title="User talk:Lightburst">talk</a>) 21:46, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b> total <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NPOL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NPOL">WP:NPOL</a> fail and now that we've included details of his malfeasance in the stub, a negative <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BLP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BLP">WP:BLP</a> for a relatively private individual. <a href="/wiki/User:SportingFlyer" title="User:SportingFlyer">SportingFlyer</a> <i><span style="font-size:small; vertical-align:top;"><a href="/wiki/User_talk:SportingFlyer" title="User talk:SportingFlyer">T</a></span></i>·<i><span style="font-size:small; vertical-align:bottom;"><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/SportingFlyer" title="Special:Contributions/SportingFlyer">C</a></span></i> 07:30, 13 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>Editors use the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BLP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BLP">WP:BLP</a> argument far too often. Subject is not a relatively private individual...was a Erie County Legislator (during his bitter campaign there was a <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://buffalonews.com/2001/11/01/olma-challenge-of-dale-dismissed/">NY State Supreme Court decision</a> about Dale's residency), he was a Village attorney, he had a very public conviction and 2 very public appeals, one in 2013 and another to the New York State Court of Appeals. Was convicted and served time for his crime. Notable per <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:RS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RS">WP:RS</a>. Are we going to scrub court records and news articles from the public domain? We do not serve our readers with deletion. <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ATD" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ATD">WP:ATD</a> <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CONTINUEDCOVERAGE" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:CONTINUEDCOVERAGE">WP:CONTINUEDCOVERAGE</a> <a href="/wiki/User:Lightburst" title="User:Lightburst">Lightburst</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Lightburst" title="User talk:Lightburst">talk</a>) 13:16, 13 August 2019 (UTC)
<dl><dd>The notability test for local politicians is not just the ability to demonstrate a local profile in their own local area — <i>every</i> local politician can <i>always</i> claim to be locally prominent, by the very definition of being a local politician. The notability test for municipal or county level politicians, the thing that has to be satisfied in order to claim that they're "high profile" enough to warrant a Wikipedia article, is the ability to demonstrate that their profile and/or importance <i>transcended</i> the purely local and turned into a <i>nationalized</i> profile. <a href="/wiki/User:Bearcat" title="User:Bearcat">Bearcat</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bearcat" title="User talk:Bearcat">talk</a>) 16:53, 15 August 2019 (UTC)</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Weak delete</b> Even taking into account the controversies about his disbarment and jail sentence, I couldn't find any national-level coverage of any of this beyond the paltry local Buffalo coverage. Whatever exists doesn't seem to point to a reason why this suburban disgraced politician (who served for only a year) deserves an encyclopedia article. <a href="/wiki/User:StonyBrook" title="User:StonyBrook">StonyBrook</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:StonyBrook" title="User talk:StonyBrook">talk</a>) 00:59, 14 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<p>The result was <b>keep</b>. As far as notability is concerned, there is no rule anywhere that says that non-English sources do not contribute to notability. <a href="/wiki/User:Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="User:Jo-Jo Eumerus">Jo-Jo Eumerus</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="User talk:Jo-Jo Eumerus">talk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Special:CentralAuth/Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="Special:CentralAuth/Jo-Jo Eumerus">contributions</a>) 14:40, 19 August 2019 (UTC)

<small>Please add new comments below this notice. Thanks, <a href="/wiki/User:Yunshui" title="User:Yunshui">Yunshui</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Yunshui" title="User talk:Yunshui"><sup style="font-size:90%">雲</sup></a><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Yunshui" title="Special:Contributions/Yunshui"><sub style="font-size:90%">水</sub></a> 09:57, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></div>
<ul><li><b>Keep</b> A Google News search throws up multiple hits. I've added two pieces that look good quality to the article and there appears to be more available. <a href="/wiki/User:Bondegezou" title="User:Bondegezou">Bondegezou</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bondegezou" title="User talk:Bondegezou">talk</a>) 10:30, 14 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>Nope. Not in English, because I checked. What language do you speak? This is the English Wikipedia. Although the documentation doesn't forbid foreign sources, it does discourage them. For one reason, machine translations are terrible. For another, most readers of the English Wikpedia speak English and English alone. Therefore it is a real slap in the face to expect them to read a language they don't understand.<br /><a href="/wiki/User:Vmavanti" title="User:Vmavanti">Vmavanti</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Vmavanti" title="User talk:Vmavanti">talk</a>) 15:38, 14 August 2019 (UTC)
<dl><dd>As per <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NONENG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NONENG">WP:NONENG</a>, a Wikipedia policy, while English-language citations are <i>preferred</i> where possible, "Citations to non-English reliable sources are allowed on the English Wikipedia." If non-English sources exist, that satisfies notability criteria.</dd>
<dd>Your own tone, comments like "What language do you speak?" and "a real slap in the face", are inappropriate and I would remind you of <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:AGF" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:AGF">WP:AGF</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Bondegezou" title="User:Bondegezou">Bondegezou</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bondegezou" title="User talk:Bondegezou">talk</a>) 22:10, 14 August 2019 (UTC)
<dl><dd>On the contrary, my tone is completely appropriate and my arguments are sound. Let's stay on the ground. If you think I am being sarcastic when I asked what language you speak, you are reading between the lines. If the subject in front of us is foreign language sources, then of course it's logical to ask what language you speak, esp. if one is enthusiastic about foreign language sources and has recommended them. My question was serious and stated in plain language. My point about favoring foreign language sources OVER English is also serious and not all sarcastic or a put down. Imagine a Wikipedia article in English where all the sources are in a different language. That's a slap in the face of English-speaking readers because they have no way of using those sources. You repeated a point I already made about policy, and there was no need to do that, so I could question your tone but I won't. Let's try to stay on Earth and speak plainly. You said "A Google News search throws up multiple hits" but you neglected to mention that every one of those hits is in a language other than English. I return to the point I made earlier: English is preferred. Given that it is preferred, let us use English on the English Wikipedia nearly all the time for the benefit of English speaking readers, hundreds of millions, rather than privilege those few who happen to speak other languages. There are other Wikipedias in other languages. No one is being marginalized except English speaking readers.<br /><a href="/wiki/User:Vmavanti" title="User:Vmavanti">Vmavanti</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Vmavanti" title="User talk:Vmavanti">talk</a>) 02:18, 15 August 2019 (UTC)
<dl><dd>Yes, English-language sources are preferred. However, that is irrelevant for the purposes of determining notability. If there are reliable sources, then <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> is satisfied and the article should not be deleted. It does not matter what language those sources are in with respect to a decision about the article's notability. Your comments have no basis in Wikipedia policy.</dd>
<dd>Where possible, we should replace non-English-language sourcing with English-language sourcing. Where not possible, we use non-English-language sourcing. I have added sources to the article. I couldn't see any English-language sources containing the same material, so I used non-English-language sources. As per policy.</dd>
<dd>What language <i>I</i> speak is irrelevant. See <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ADHOM" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ADHOM">WP:ADHOM</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Bondegezou" title="User:Bondegezou">Bondegezou</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bondegezou" title="User talk:Bondegezou">talk</a>) 11:18, 15 August 2019 (UTC)
<dl><dd>I consider false accusations and distorting comments acts of incivility. Fortunately, facts and solving problems are more important to me than the futile attempt to control whether other people are nice or good. There's no point in repeating the points I have made, and there's no point in your repeating points I have made. Sources are necessarily at the heart of notability. Therefore the language of sources is relevant, especially when there are few sources available or when all the sources available are in a foreign language. There's really no way to avoid common sense, even when you are interpreting policy. Your language is relevant if it influences your judgment about what sources are acceptable. The language that readers of English Wikipedia speak—English—is most important of all. Any writer, editor, teacher, or Wikipedia policy pedant will tell you to keep in mind the audience first over one's own preferences. Let's put the interests of readers first. That is policy.<br /><a href="/wiki/User:Vmavanti" title="User:Vmavanti">Vmavanti</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Vmavanti" title="User talk:Vmavanti">talk</a>) 17:49, 15 August 2019 (UTC)</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<ul><li><ul><li>Foreign language sources are perfecly acceptable, particularly for non-English subjects, and using google translate is easier for readers than tracking down off-line sources <a href="/wiki/User:Atlantic306" title="User:Atlantic306">Atlantic306</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Atlantic306" title="User talk:Atlantic306">talk</a>) 17:55, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Comment</b> I have expanded the article further, with citations. <a href="/wiki/User:Bondegezou" title="User:Bondegezou">Bondegezou</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bondegezou" title="User talk:Bondegezou">talk</a>) 09:57, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd>Google Translate can't even get the pronouns right. I have seen that many times. I can't even persuade you to use colons instead of asterisks. Do you really think the asterisk is an easier key to hit than the colon? Of course it isn't. Do you think it looks better? Of course it doesn't. When you use an asterisk, you get two large black dots with a gap between them. Debate privileges reason, but if people can't be reasonable about something as simple and obvious as using colons on Talk pages, there will be no real debate. Let's not make this another "Do it my way just because..." power struggle. The mature, down to earth method is to argue these points and consider them carefully and thoughtfully.<br />–<a href="/wiki/User:Vmavanti" title="User:Vmavanti">Vmavanti</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Vmavanti" title="User talk:Vmavanti">talk</a>) 23:52, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</dd></dl></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Keep</b> I’ve added a bit more material and a couple of refs. There is clearly enough in German to support the notability of the subject, and I’m afraid the idea that we need to avoid sources from languages other than English is completely wrong. <a href="/wiki/User:Mccapra" title="User:Mccapra">Mccapra</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mccapra" title="User talk:Mccapra">talk</a>) 04:19, 19 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<dl><dd><i>The above discussion is preserved as an archive of the debate. <b style="color:red">Please do not modify it.</b> Subsequent comments should be made on the appropriate discussion page (such as the article's <a href="/wiki/Help:Using_talk_pages" class="mw-redirect" title="Help:Using talk pages">talk page</a> or in a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Deletion_review" title="Wikipedia:Deletion review">deletion review</a>). No further edits should be made to this page.</i></dd></dl></div>
<div class="boilerplate afd vfd xfd-closed" style="background-color: #F3F9FF; margin: 2em 0 0 0; padding: 0 10px 0 10px; border: 1px solid #AAAAAA;">
<dl><dd><i>The following discussion is an archived debate of the proposed deletion of the article below. <span style="color:red"><b>Please do not modify it.</b></span> Subsequent comments should be made on the appropriate discussion page (such as the article's <a href="/wiki/Help:Using_talk_pages" class="mw-redirect" title="Help:Using talk pages">talk page</a> or in a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Deletion_review" title="Wikipedia:Deletion review">deletion review</a>). No further edits should be made to this page.</i></dd></dl>
<p>The result was <b>no consensus</b>. Seems like there are a few issues here. The first is whether this is a vexatious renomination of an already kept article; it seems like there is no consensus for this idea owing to e.g a deletion review on the last deletion nomination that explicitly allowed for renomination.
</p><p>The second is whether there is enough coverage of the phrase to establish notability and to defeat <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:DICDEF" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:DICDEF">WP:DICDEF</a> concerns, and whether the available sourcing is adequate for this or merely a bunch of unrelated things <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:SYNTH" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:SYNTH">synthesized</a> into an article. Most of the commenters are addressing this question, the headcount is almost evenly split and while most keep arguments do not mention any source, some of them (such as GirthSummit) do point out the existence of potentially valid sources and it's not clear that they have been conclusively refuted. My sense is that there is no consensus due to several uncontested sources and some statements by delete arguments that may or may not refute the keep arguments, as well as disagreement on whether some usages are suitable proof of notability where both sides have raised rational arguments. There are some uncontested concerns that at least part of the article is <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:OR" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:OR">WP:OR</a> but that does not automatically establish a reason for deletion; sometimes such issues can be resolved solely by editing.
</p><p>Finally, Uncle G has proposed a rewrite/repurpose of the topic. It seems like it has gained a little support and no explicit opposition, but by my reading just not enough support to classify the rewrite/repurpose as a consensus. Thus I'll play safe and call the conclusion "'no consensus"', but that Uncle G's proposal should be further considered e.g in a talk page discussion or just by bold editing including redirection. And editors may want to address any <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:OR" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:OR">WP:OR</a>/<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:SYNTH" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:SYNTH">WP:SYNTH</a> issues the article may have, as the concerns about the adequacy of the current content are reasonably supported. <a href="/wiki/User:Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="User:Jo-Jo Eumerus">Jo-Jo Eumerus</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="User talk:Jo-Jo Eumerus">talk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Special:CentralAuth/Jo-Jo_Eumerus" title="Special:CentralAuth/Jo-Jo Eumerus">contributions</a>) 15:28, 19 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>

<p>This is a non-notable term. Most of the references used in the article are examples of it being used (ie that <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ITEXISTS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ITEXISTS">WP:ITEXISTS</a>) but this doesn't make it notable: see <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:EDPN" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:EDPN">WP:EDPN</a>. Some of the references are about the stereotype of British judges being out of touch with the common man, and use the term 'popular beat combo' as an example, but this does not amount to <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:SIGCOV" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:SIGCOV">significant coverage</a> of the term itself. <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOT#DICT" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOT">WP:NOT#DICT</a> etc.<br />It is not Wikipedia's function to record every term or phrase that is used in a humourous context: <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IINFO" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:IINFO">WP:IINFO</a>. We areonly here to cover topics which meet our <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:N" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:N">notability policy's threshold</a> of having "received significant coverage, directly and in detail, in reliable sources".<br />Please note that the page was nominated for deletion earlier this year but the result of 'keep' was <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Deletion_review/Log/2019_May_8" title="Wikipedia:Deletion review/Log/2019 May 8">held</a> to be "questionable" given the high number of <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ATA" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ATA">non-policy-compliant</a> !votes. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Amisom&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Amisom (page does not exist)">Amisom</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Amisom" title="User talk:Amisom">talk</a>) 09:35, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>

As for the supposed case against, it's quite false. It's clear that the late <a href="/wiki/Marcel_Berlins" title="Marcel Berlins">Marcel Berlins</a> put some effort in researching this and this is well-documented and sourced. <li>I have been doing some reading.<p>First, as far as Wikipedia is concerned we can verifiably source this to <a href="/wiki/James_Pickles" title="James Pickles">James Pickles</a>, because there are umpteen obituaries of xem asserting this. If this were all that there were to this, I would suggest a merger there, for being an anecdote about M. Pickles that was so significantly representative of xem that it made it into xyr obituaries <i>ahead</i> of the person whom it turns out <i>really did</i> once scrub things for a living.</p><p>However, if one does the usual AFD trick of phrase matching with Google Books and does not actually <i>read</i> <a href="#CITEREFDavies2018">Davies 2018</a> one will miss the scholarship by a large distance. Davies is talking about <i>judicial anecdotes</i>, and makes the point several times over, in a chapter which <i>does not</i> document this one anecdote in depth other than to hold it up as an example of how such things follow a narrative script of an ″out of touch judge″ stereotype, that such anecdotes are often misattributed or indeed non-factual.</p><p>(If you think that ″stuffy reactionary conservative″ is the British newspaper stereotype of judges, be aware that there are sources out there &#8212; e.g. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781841134956" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 9781841134956</a> p.51 &#8212; that note how this stereotype changed to quite the opposite in the 1990s, so if your view of this comes from a satirical magazine from the 1960s it's <i>that magazine</i> that is now out of touch. &#9786; Also, the <i>Wales Online</i> article that Pontificalibus points to is a fairly bad source. It is fairly reliably sourced that <i>journalists like that</i> more interested in sensationalism than fact <i>invented</i> the ″Is Gazza an opera?″ question and that was not what was actually asked.)</p><p>The rest of the book that <a href="#CITEREFDavies2018">Davies 2018</a> is in also discusses <i>judicial humour</i>, including judges making jokes. To counter Pommiepedia bias, it is worth nothing that there is a significant body of <i>Australian</i> work on that subject including (for starters) <a href="/wiki/Social_Science_Research_Network" title="Social Science Research Network">SSRN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://ssrn.com/abstract=2623443">2623443</a>.</p><p>I think that we could rename and refactor this into an article on <a href="/w/index.php?title=Judicial_anecdotes&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judicial anecdotes (page does not exist)">judicial anecdotes</a>, not least because there is an <i>anecdote</i> entry in Gibson's <i>Pocket A&#8211;Z of Criminal Justice</i> (albeit a very short one); retaining the link to M. Pickles and using this as <i>an example</i>, which is really what it is, not a subject in its own right.</p><p><a href="/wiki/User:Uncle_G" title="User:Uncle G">Uncle G</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Uncle_G" title="User talk:Uncle G">talk</a>) 18:08, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p><ul><li>I rather doubt it originates with Pickles, who only became a proper circuit judge in 1976, which I think is some time after the phrase became current. .divbox-teal{background-color:#008080;border:1px solid #40e0d0}.mw-parser-output .divbox-thistle{background-color:#d8bfd8;font-size:11pt;border:1px solid #7d00b3}.mw-parser-output .divbox-tt{background-color:transparent;color:darkblue;border:1px solid grey}.mw-parser-output .divbox-wdl{background-color:#cee3f6;border:1px solid #cee3f6}.mw-parser-output <p><b><a href="/w/index.php?title=Judicial_anecdotes&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judicial anecdotes (page does not exist)">judicial anecdotes</a></b> are <a href="/wiki/Anecdotes" class="mw-redirect" title="Anecdotes">anecdotes</a> told about judges.
</p><p>Unlike <a href="/w/index.php?title=Judge_jokes&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judge jokes (page does not exist)">judge jokes</a>, judicial anecdotes are intended to be taken as true; however, that is often not the case as they frequently are misattributed or misquoted.
They are also not necessarily humourous in intent; as often the intent is to exhibit the character of the person about whom the anecdote is told.
</p><p>One such was widely attributed to <a href="/wiki/James_Pickles" title="James Pickles">James Pickles</a> in his obituaries.
Anecdotally, he asked "Who are The Beatles?"; to which a barrister answered "I believe they are a popular beat combo, <a href="/wiki/M%27lud" class="mw-redirect" title="M&#39;lud">m'lud</a>."
This anecdote demonstrates one facet of such anecdotes, namely that they play into stereotypes.
Here, the stereotype is that of a conservative, reactionary, out of touch judge.
This stereotype was common in British newspapers in the 1960s and 1970s, albeit that the 1980s and 1990s saw it entirely reversed as a Conservative Party government saw many of its actions thwarted by judicial rulings, prompting the newspapers (those that supported the Conservative Party, that is) to lampoon judges with the opposite stereotype of being excessively liberal and trendy.
</p><p>It also demonstrates the problems of correct attribution.
<a href="/wiki/Marcel_Berlins" title="Marcel Berlins">Marcel Berlins</a>, legal correspondent for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i> newspaper, failed in his attempt to track down where, preciseley, this was said, when, and by whom.
He twice offered, with no result, a magnum of champagne to anyone who successfully did so.
(The later obituaries did not say where and when Justice Pickles wa supposed too have said this, and the accepted view that the anecdote dates from the 1960s pre-dates Pickles' joining the circuit in the 1970s.)
</p><p>Anecdotes can involve misreporting.
Anecdotally, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Jeremiah_Le_Roy_Harman&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Jeremiah Le Roy Harman (page does not exist)">Jeremiah Le Roy Harman</a>, in a case involving <a href="/wiki/Paul_Gascoigne" title="Paul Gascoigne">Paul Gascoigne</a> who was widely known as ″Gazza″, asked ″Is Gazza an opera?″.
This was, however, a construction by journalists looking to sensationalize, Gascoigne's life being a favourite subject of the newspapers of the time.
In fact Judge Harmon had actually asked ″Isn't there an operetta called <i><a href="/wiki/La_Gazza_Ladra" class="mw-redirect" title="La Gazza Ladra">La Gazza Ladra</a></i>?″.
</p><p>Given Gascoigne's nickname and his then image of being a ″lad″ this may have been an instance of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Judicial_humour&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judicial humour (page does not exist)">judicial humour</a>, which has a tendency towards puns and witticisms, falling flat because of its sheer obscurity.
Judicial anecdotes also exemplify such things; another such being an anecdote related about <a href="/w/index.php?title=A._H._Bodley&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="A. H. Bodley (page does not exist)">A. H. Bodley</a> who, in reponse to a witness, a young lift-boy, describing a <a href="/wiki/Mezzanine_floor" class="mw-redirect" title="Mezzanine floor">mezzanine floor</a> as a ″Mazarin floor″ in testimony, noted that ″It is but a cardinal error.″, an obscure reference to <a href="/wiki/Cardinal_Mazarin" title="Cardinal Mazarin">Cardinal Mazarin</a> that the lift-boy and others present were unlikely to have understood.
</p><p>Publishing collections of such anecdotes has been a regular activity since the 19th century.
Two such recent collections are <i>Miscellany at Law</i> &#8230;
</p>
<dl><dd><i>&#8230; and so on, you can see where this is going.</i></dd></dl>

<p><b><a href="/w/index.php?title=Judicial_humour&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judicial humour (page does not exist)">judicial humour</a></b> is the use of humour by judges, in court, in judicial opinions and otherwise.
</p>

</div><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r890676480"/><div class="metadata divbox divbox-brown"><div class="divbox-heading"></div>
<p><b><a href="/w/index.php?title=Judge_jokes&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Judge jokes (page does not exist)">judge jokes</a></b> are jokes told about judges.
</p><p>In the United States, such jokes differ from <a href="/wiki/Lawyer_jokes" class="mw-redirect" title="Lawyer jokes">lawyer jokes</a> in two ways: they are rarer and they are less critical of their targets.
</p>

<li><b>Redirect</b> Agree with the previous response. I've heard of the expression and understand the joke, such as it is, but it is not in wide use. <ul><li>FWIW (which is admittedly very little), I heard and used this phrase before I ever read Private Eye - indeed, before I got involved in this discussion, I didn't know that it was particularly associated with PI, I just thought it was a thing that everybody knew about. Full disclosure: I do now subscribe to PI, but I only started doing that in my thirties, whereas the 'popular beat combo' I sang in during my university days described itself as such in our side-splittingly ironic posters. People seemed to get the joke, but maybe they were all PI readers. <a href="/wiki/User:Girth_Summit" title="User:Girth Summit"><span style="font-family:Impact;color:#294;">Girth</span><span style="font-family:Impact;color:#42c;">Summit</span></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Girth_Summit" title="User talk:Girth Summit"><sub style="font-family:script;color:blue;"> (blether)</sub></a> 20:00, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li>
<li><b>Comment</b>. Above: "it has been used so much as to become notable ... it's the repetition of the performance which makes it"; "it is not in wide use"; "It is NOT 'a very common phrase in widespread use in the UK'". No evidence seems to be provided for either its claimed wide use or its claimed rarity. So, <i>is</i> it widely used? I can't provide a quick answer, but I can suggest how widely it was used in Britain from circa 1980 to 1993. The <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.english-corpora.org/bnc/">British National Corpus</a>, which covers this period, has no hits, zero, for "popular beat combo". For comparison: "tired and emotional", 12 hits; "since sliced bread", 11; "crocodile tears", 22; "economical with the truth", 16; "mistakes were made", 11; "wrong kind of snow", 3. -- <a href="/wiki/User:Hoary" title="User:Hoary">Hoary</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hoary" title="User talk:Hoary">talk</a>) 22:42, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Comment</b>. Wot, no comment on my comment? It could be claimed that BNC is dated, and that the popularity of "popular beat combo" has leapt up since 1993. I therefore looked in <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.english-corpora.org/iweb/">the iWeb corpus</a>, a humongous corpus compiled from either 2017 or 2018 (Davies' own explanations disagree on this), from websites that may well predate this but can be expected to postdate 1993. There's no limitation to British sources, but British sources are included. And so: "popular beat combo" gets 18 hits; "tired and emotional", 148 hits; "since sliced bread", 2407; "crocodile tears", 1032; "economical with the truth", 276; "mistakes were made", 1644; "wrong kind of snow", 21. -- <a href="/wiki/User:Hoary" title="User:Hoary">Hoary</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hoary" title="User talk:Hoary">talk</a>) 01:36, 19 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b>. I see no evidence that this phrase has ever had more than the most minor use. In its current state, the article tells us that <span style="color:olive">The deliberately out-dated cliche may be used as an ironic or journalistic synonym, or by someone to denigrate a pop group referred to, or may be used of another person's views to imply that they are "out of touch". It may also be used to ridicule legalese, antiquated courtroom practices, and eccentric judges.</span> "May be", "or may be", "may also be" used -- but very rarely <i>is</i> used (and above, I present the numbers to demonstrate this). Not notable. -- <a href="/wiki/User:Hoary" title="User:Hoary">Hoary</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hoary" title="User talk:Hoary">talk</a>) 01:36, 19 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li class="mw-empty-elt"></li></ul>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Language" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Language">list of Language-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Hoary" title="User:Hoary">Hoary</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hoary" title="User talk:Hoary">talk</a>) 02:48, 19 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Discussions_missing_the_point">Discussions missing the point</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Popular_beat_combo_(2nd_nomination)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-9" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<ul><li><b>Comment</b> - am I missing the point here in these discussions? The article is not mainly about pop music or about courtroom exchanges, but about a very common phrase in widespread use in the UK - in the same way that "<a href="/wiki/The_wrong_type_of_snow" title="The wrong type of snow">The wrong type of snow</a>" ("wrong type of...") is often not used to refer to the weather. What needs to be done to get this across clearly? Is it the muddled intro sentence that needs re-writing? --<a href="/wiki/User:Mervyn" title="User:Mervyn">Mervyn</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mervyn" title="User talk:Mervyn">talk</a>) 08:20, 16 August 2019 (UTC)
<ul><li>The problem is that Wikipedia isn’t a dictionary and the phrase isn’t encyclopedically notable. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Amisom&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Amisom (page does not exist)">Amisom</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Amisom" title="User talk:Amisom">talk</a>) 08:29, 16 August 2019 (UTC)
<ul><li>Having already ivoted, and seeing no reason at all to change my response to this, I thought I'd check for <a href="/wiki/Leaves_on_the_line" class="mw-redirect" title="Leaves on the line">Leaves on the line</a>. -<a href="/wiki/User:Roxy_the_dog" title="User:Roxy the dog"><b>Roxy,</b> <small>the dog</small>.</a> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Roxy_the_dog" title="User talk:Roxy the dog"><b>wooF</b></a> 08:50, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li>
<li>The content about the possible origin of the phrase shows it is far more involved than a dictionary entry. --<a href="/wiki/User:Mervyn" title="User:Mervyn">Mervyn</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mervyn" title="User talk:Mervyn">talk</a>) 10:42, 16 August 2019 (UTC)
<ul><li>I could write a very invovled article about my dog. It doesn't mean that the article should be kept. The question is whether it meets the GNG, not whether <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ITSINTERESTING" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ITSINTERESTING">WP:ITSINTERESTING</a>. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Amisom&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Amisom (page does not exist)">Amisom</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Amisom" title="User talk:Amisom">talk</a>) 10:55, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li>
<li>It is NOT "a very common phrase in widespread use in the UK" - that's why there aren't any sources discussing its use in detail, and why the article is confusing. <a href="/wiki/The_wrong_type_of_snow" title="The wrong type of snow">The wrong type of snow</a> specifies multiple sources discussing usage of that phrase from its origin to its cliched use in wider context - however we don't have that here. ----<a href="/wiki/User:Pontificalibus" title="User:Pontificalibus"><strong style="color:#555555">Pontificalibus</strong></a> 11:31, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li>The wrong type of snow includes several references to books and articles that deal with "the wrong kind of snow" as a topic, rather than just in passing. While I will admit to having only scratched the surface of the possible sources on <a href="/wiki/Popular_beat_combo" title="Popular beat combo">popular beat combo</a>, there do not seem to be any that use it as their subject, all simply use it in passing. That said, does anyone have access to <i>Rules Britannia: the 101 Essential Questions of Britishness Answered, from how to keep a stiff upper lip to who ate all the pies</i>? If you do, can you check if it has a section on "Popular beat combo"? Google books doesn't think it does, but it is worth a check. <a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Rockphed&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Rockphed (page does not exist)">Rockphed</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Rockphed" title="User talk:Rockphed">talk</a>) 11:45, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul></li>
<li>If the claim is DICDEF, let's define accurately. Popular beat combo, n., humorous or ironic. Chiefly British. "The term is regarded as being archaic and overly formal in relation to the subject matter, and is intended to reflect the way in which an old-fashioned or older person would refer to a contemporary pop group." (<a href="/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary" title="Oxford English Dictionary">OED</a>) <a href="/wiki/User:Drmies" title="User:Drmies">Drmies</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Drmies" title="User talk:Drmies">talk</a>) 16:17, 16 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<p>Non-notable cricket league. Note that <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CRIN" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:CRIN">WP:CRIN</a> only covers "players, teams, venues or matches". Accordingly, <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NSPORT" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NSPORT">WP:NSPORT</a> relies on <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a>, which the subject fails to meet. Coverage for this event which is due to take place later this year is exclusively promotional at the moment. If it happens, and if it garners more significant coverage at the time, then an article will probably be suitable, but right now, this does not have significant, in-depth coverage, and appears to fail <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CRYSTAL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:CRYSTAL">WP:CRYSTAL</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Harrias" title="User:Harrias"><span style="color:#00cc33">Harrias</span></a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Harrias" title="User talk:Harrias"><span style="color:#009900">talk</span></a></sup> 08:59, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Cricket" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Cricket">list of Cricket-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Harrias" title="User:Harrias"><span style="color:#00cc33">Harrias</span></a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Harrias" title="User talk:Harrias"><span style="color:#009900">talk</span></a></sup> 08:59, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd>
<dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Qatar" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Qatar">list of Qatar-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Harrias" title="User:Harrias"><span style="color:#00cc33">Harrias</span></a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Harrias" title="User talk:Harrias"><span style="color:#009900">talk</span></a></sup> 08:59, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Delete</b>. Per nom. This league simply isn't notable and has poor coverage. It would be nice for tournament articles to be restricted to first-class/List A/Twenty20 cricket, or otherwise historically notable, e.g. the Minor Counties Championship or the Hawke Cup. <a href="/wiki/User:AssociateAffiliate" title="User:AssociateAffiliate">StickyWicket</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:AssociateAffiliate" title="User talk:AssociateAffiliate">talk</a>) 22:17, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Richard_Lorenzen"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Richard Lorenzen (page does not exist)">Richard Lorenzen</a></span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;section=T-1" title="Edit section: ">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<dl><dd><span id="Richard_Lorenzen"></span><span class="plainlinks nourlexpansion lx"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Richard Lorenzen (page does not exist)">Richard Lorenzen</a> (<a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit">edit</a>&#160;&#124; <a href="/w/index.php?title=Talk:Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Talk:Richard Lorenzen (page does not exist)">talk</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=history">history</a><span class="sysop-show">&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=protect">protect</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=delete">delete</a></span>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere/Richard_Lorenzen&amp;limit=999">links</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=watch">watch</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Log&amp;page=Richard+Lorenzen">logs</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="//tools.wmflabs.org/pageviews?pages=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;project=en.wikipedia.org">views</a>)</span> – (<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Richard_Lorenzen" title="Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Richard Lorenzen">View AfD</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <span class="plainlinks"><a class="external text" href="https://tools.wmflabs.org/jackbot/snottywong/cgi-bin/votecounter.cgi?page=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Richard_Lorenzen">Stats</a></span>)</dd>
<dd>(<span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">Google</a> (<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-wikipedia">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+site:news.google.com/newspapers&amp;source=newspapers">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/search?safe=off&amp;tbs=sur:fmc&amp;tbm=isch&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-site:wikipedia.org+-site:wikimedia.org">free images</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/custom?hl=en&amp;cx=007734830908295939403%3Agalkqgoksq0&amp;cof=FORID%3A13%3BAH%3Aleft%3BCX%3AWikipedia%2520Reference%2520Search&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">WP refs</a>)&#160;<b>·</b> <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Free_English_newspaper_sources">FENS</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.nytimes.com/search/%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">NYT</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://wikipedialibrary.wmflabs.org/partners/">TWL</a></span>)</dd></dl>
<p>Self promotional puff piece full of citations that primarily consist of paid articles and little to no organic content. Fails to meet standards set forth in <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BIO" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BIO">WP:BIO</a>. History of edits are dodgy and some seem to be from SPAs. Notability guidelines are not met and the page is just a litany of facts surrounding the basic biographical information of a non-notable individual from an average family. Richard Lorenzen doesn’t meet <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> and in some instances violates <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BLP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BLP">WP:BLP</a> as there is a substantial amount of unsourced information.
</p><p>The article in and of itself seems to be largely self-promotional and may be penned by the subject himself. He’s a small business owner with a self published book and his desire for self-promotion with titles such as “philanthropist” (no sources) and others clearly violates the letter and spirit of GNG or any low standard set for special notability.
</p><p>In-depth internet research demonstrates that while Richard Lorenzen has indeed been quoted in a few newspapers and publications, this does not immediately usher one past the threshold of the notability guidelines.
</p><p>Also, the page was nominated for deletion in the past, and that AfD tag was suspiciously removed. <a href="/wiki/User:Fifthavenuebrands" title="User:Fifthavenuebrands">Fifthavenuebrands</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Fifthavenuebrands" title="User talk:Fifthavenuebrands">talk</a>) 07:52, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>

<ul><li><b>Delete</b>. Fails <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ANYBIO" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ANYBIO">WP:ANYBIO</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NPOL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NPOL">WP:NPOL</a>. Promotion piece.<a href="/wiki/User:CASSIOPEIA" title="User:CASSIOPEIA"><b style="font-family:Georgia;font-size:80%;color:#FA0"> CASSIOPEIA</b></a><sup>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:CASSIOPEIA" title="User talk:CASSIOPEIA"><b style="#0000FF">talk</b></a>)</sup> 09:31, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<dl><dd><span id="Richard_Lorenzen"></span><span class="plainlinks nourlexpansion lx"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Richard Lorenzen (page does not exist)">Richard Lorenzen</a> (<a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit">edit</a>&#160;&#124; <a href="/w/index.php?title=Talk:Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Talk:Richard Lorenzen (page does not exist)">talk</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=history">history</a><span class="sysop-show">&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=protect">protect</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=delete">delete</a></span>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere/Richard_Lorenzen&amp;limit=999">links</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;action=watch">watch</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Log&amp;page=Richard+Lorenzen">logs</a>&#160;&#124; <a class="external text" href="//tools.wmflabs.org/pageviews?pages=Richard_Lorenzen&amp;project=en.wikipedia.org">views</a>)</span> – (<a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Richard_Lorenzen" title="Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Richard Lorenzen">View AfD</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <span class="plainlinks"><a class="external text" href="https://tools.wmflabs.org/jackbot/snottywong/cgi-bin/votecounter.cgi?page=Wikipedia:Articles_for_deletion/Richard_Lorenzen">Stats</a></span>)</dd>
<dd>(<span class="plainlinks"><i>Find sources:</i>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">Google</a> (<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-wikipedia">books</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-wikipedia">news</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.google.com/search?&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+site:news.google.com/newspapers&amp;source=newspapers">newspapers</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">scholar</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/search?safe=off&amp;tbs=sur:fmc&amp;tbm=isch&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22+-site:wikipedia.org+-site:wikimedia.org">free images</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.google.com/custom?hl=en&amp;cx=007734830908295939403%3Agalkqgoksq0&amp;cof=FORID%3A13%3BAH%3Aleft%3BCX%3AWikipedia%2520Reference%2520Search&amp;q=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">WP refs</a>)&#160;<b>·</b> <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Free_English_newspaper_sources">FENS</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Richard+Lorenzen%22&amp;acc=on&amp;wc=on">JSTOR</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.nytimes.com/search/%22Richard+Lorenzen%22">NYT</a>&#160;<b>·</b> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://wikipedialibrary.wmflabs.org/partners/">TWL</a></span>)</dd></dl>
<p>Self promotional puff piece full of citations that primarily consist of paid articles and little to no organic content. Fails to meet standards set forth in <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BIO" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BIO">WP:BIO</a>. History of edits are dodgy and some seem to be from SPAs. Notability guidelines are not met and the page is just a litany of facts surrounding the basic biographical information of a non-notable individual from an average family. Richard Lorenzen doesn’t meet <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:GNG" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:GNG">WP:GNG</a> and in some instances violates <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BLP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BLP">WP:BLP</a> as there is a substantial amount of unsourced information.
</p><p>The article in and of itself seems to be largely self-promotional and may be penned by the subject himself. He’s a small business owner with a self published book and his desire for self-promotion with titles such as “philanthropist” (no sources) and others clearly violates the letter and spirit of GNG or any low standard set for special notability.
</p><p>In-depth internet research demonstrates that while Richard Lorenzen has indeed been quoted in a few newspapers and publications, this does not immediately usher one past the threshold of the notability guidelines.
</p><p>Also, the page was nominated for deletion in the past, and that AfD tag was suspiciously removed. <a href="/wiki/User:Fifthavenuebrands" title="User:Fifthavenuebrands">Fifthavenuebrands</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Fifthavenuebrands" title="User talk:Fifthavenuebrands">talk</a>) 07:52, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
</p>

<ul><li><b>Delete</b>. Fails <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ANYBIO" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ANYBIO">WP:ANYBIO</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NPOL" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NPOL">WP:NPOL</a>. <ul><li><b>Speedied.</b> Blatant COI. <a href="/wiki/User:Deb" title="User:Deb">Deb</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Deb" title="User talk:Deb">talk</a>) 11:15, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

While the article is full of puffery and the grammar as is is terrible, both of these issues could be fixed. But from what I can see most of the references are indeed primary, and from what I can find—very, very little—it looks like Prevale has barely charted on any charts. <b><a href="/wiki/User:Ss112" title="User:Ss112"><span style="color: #FF6347;">Ss</span></a><small><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Ss112" title="User talk:Ss112"><span style="color: #1E90FF;">112</span></a></small></b> 15:25, 13 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<li><b>Keep</b>, as there seems to be enough available to show notability. Although I wouldn't disagree if a page was created for the V/STOL projects, and this material was merged there.<a href="/wiki/User:Onel5969" title="User:Onel5969"><b><span style="color:#536895;">Onel</span><span style="color:#ffb300;">5969</span></b></a> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Onel5969" title="User talk:Onel5969"><i style="color:blue">TT me</i></a></sup> 11:04, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><s><b>Keep</b> - the de-Wiki article shows that GNG can be met, and a decent article written.</s> Struck - woefully lacking sources. <a href="/wiki/User:Mjroots" title="User:Mjroots">Mjroots</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mjroots" title="User talk:Mjroots">talk</a>) 14:49, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Keep</b>. Seems enough to justify an article, subject to expansion with more sources to meet GNG. Otherwise, a merge should be considered. I think deletion at the moment would in haste. <a href="/wiki/User:No_Great_Shaker" title="User:No Great Shaker">No Great Shaker</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:No_Great_Shaker" title="User talk:No Great Shaker">talk</a>) 15:54, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Merge</b> into <a href="/wiki/EWR_VJ_101" title="EWR VJ 101">EWR VJ 101</a> and redirect. Not enough sources out there to establish notability as an independent design project, but it is certainly part of the development history of the VJ 101. &#8212; Cheers, <a href="/wiki/User:Steelpillow" title="User:Steelpillow">Steelpillow</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Steelpillow" title="User talk:Steelpillow">Talk</a>) 18:38, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Military" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Military">list of Military-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Icewhiz" title="User:Icewhiz">Icewhiz</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Icewhiz" title="User talk:Icewhiz">talk</a>) 22:02, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd>
<dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Aviation" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Aviation">list of Aviation-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Icewhiz" title="User:Icewhiz">Icewhiz</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Icewhiz" title="User talk:Icewhiz">talk</a>) 22:02, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Merge</b> to <a href="/wiki/EWR_VJ_101" title="EWR VJ 101">EWR VJ 101</a> - this one of the two first prototypes in that project (VJ 101A by Heinkel and VJ 101B by Messerschmitt - <a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://books.google.co.il/books?id=UndDAQAAIAAJ&amp;q=%22VJ+101A%22&amp;dq=%22VJ+101A%22&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjhuvCCrf_jAhVS_CoKHcGEBIEQ6AEIMDAB">[23]</a>). While plausibly this could be a standalone (not sure regarding GNG of VJ 101A by itself - but it could meet it) - we don't need a short little <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:SPINOFF" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:SPINOFF">WP:SPINOFF</a> stub on VJ 101A while the main project is much more developed. Barring a major expansion of this 46 word article - this could easily fit in a subsection in VJ 101. <a href="/wiki/User:Icewhiz" title="User:Icewhiz">Icewhiz</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Icewhiz" title="User talk:Icewhiz">talk</a>) 07:48, 13 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Keep</b> Odd that the German and Japanese wikis have an article on this design but the English one is about to be deleted, the English WP generally leads the other wikis on aviation subjects. This is a very interesting period in aviation and the origins of aircraft that did materialise from these design projects can be traced using these articles. The German article is a good size and is sourced from FlugRevue (equivalent of the UK <i>Flight</i> magazine). The Japanese article links this source where photos of two distinct designs appear, they are either full-size mock ups or models, we don't know without further research but it is obvious that some effort and expense was involved. As I researched and created <a href="/wiki/NBMR-3" title="NBMR-3">NBMR-3</a> I would be very happy to work with the article creator to build this article. <a href="/wiki/User:Nimbus227" title="User:Nimbus227">Nimbus</a> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Nimbus227" title="User talk:Nimbus227"><span style="color:#2F4F4F;">(Cumulus</span> <span style="color:#708090;">nimbus</span> <span style="color:#D3D3D3;">floats by)</span></a> 14:33, 18 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<ul><li><b>Merge</b> into <a href="/wiki/EWR_VJ_101" title="EWR VJ 101">EWR VJ 101</a> and redirect. - From <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.comptoir-aviation.com/english/2008/01/heinkel-he-231.html">1</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.flugrevue.de/klassiker/hochleistungs-kampfflugzeug-ewr-vj-101-alle-varianten/">2</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.robertcmason.com/textdocs/GermanVSTOLFighters.pdf">3</a> and others, it seems like there were at least three designs for the He 231, the first, a <a href="/wiki/Tailsitter" class="mw-redirect" title="Tailsitter">tailsitter</a> one, the second, with internal engines only and a inlet cone for a nose, and a third one with engines on the ends of it's wings, later referred to as the VJ 101A. The current article specifies VJ 101A in its lead, but shows a diagram for the second design. I believe the first two designs never went beyond the drawing board and the third only had two miniature wind tunnel models made. As it's last version before being merged-into/succeeded by the EWR VJ 101C was referred to as the VJ 101A I feel that this should be covered in the article <a href="/wiki/EWR_VJ_101" title="EWR VJ 101">EWR VJ 101</a> and treated like the "A" variant/prototype of the VJ 101 series alongside the "B" "C" "D" and (if it exists) "E" variants/prototypes. - <a href="/wiki/User:Scio_c" title="User:Scio c">Scio c</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Scio_c" title="User talk:Scio c">talk</a>) 04:32, 19 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<ul><li><b>Delete</b> A business with outlets in only one city where the article makes no credible claim of importance or significance. Sources, which would need to be strong for businesses in particular, are a collection of a) non-reliable (see <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ORGCRIT" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ORGCRIT">WP:ORGCRIT</a>); b) routine business announcements (see <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:CORPDEPTH" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:CORPDEPTH">WP:CORPDEPTH</a>); and c) just the one feature, in <a href="/wiki/Broadsheet_(website)" title="Broadsheet (website)">Broadsheet (website)</a>, which potentially is not a reliable source. -<a href="/wiki/User:Lopifalko" title="User:Lopifalko">Lopifalko</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Lopifalko" title="User talk:Lopifalko">talk</a>) 06:01, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>
<dl><dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Food_and_drink" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Food and drink">list of Food and drink-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Shellwood" title="User:Shellwood">Shellwood</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shellwood" title="User talk:Shellwood">talk</a>) 08:46, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd>
<dd><small class="delsort-notice">Note: This discussion has been included in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Deletion_sorting/Australia" title="Wikipedia:WikiProject Deletion sorting/Australia">list of Australia-related deletion discussions</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Shellwood" title="User:Shellwood">Shellwood</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shellwood" title="User talk:Shellwood">talk</a>) 08:46, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</small></dd></dl>
<ul><li><b>Delete</b> as it seems to fail to meet the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Notability" title="Wikipedia:Notability">WP:Notability</a> criteria. <a href="/wiki/User:Ktrimi991" class="mw-redirect" title="User:Ktrimi991">Ktrimi991</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Ktrimi991" title="User talk:Ktrimi991">talk</a>) 10:36, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b>. To Lopifalko's reasoning I can add only one thing: that Broadsheet is not potentially, but certainly, a non-reliable source. <a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://www.broadsheet.com.au/melbourne/food-and-drink/fine-diner-twist-cbd">[24]</a> and <a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://www.broadsheet.com.au/melbourne/food-and-drink/article/calia-heading-chadstone">[25]</a> are back-scratching industry puff pieces. --<a href="/wiki/User:Mkativerata" class="mw-redirect" title="User:Mkativerata">Mkativerata</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mkativerata" title="User talk:Mkativerata">talk</a>) 10:39, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b> Not a single reference meets the criteria for establishing notability. Most are mentions-in-passing or routine business announcements. Topic fails GNG and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NCORP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NCORP">WP:NCORP</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:HighKing" class="mw-redirect" title="User:HighKing"><b style="font-family: Courier; color: darkgreen;"> HighKing</b></a><sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:HighKing" title="User talk:HighKing"><span style="font-family: Courier; color: #da0000;">++ </span></a></sup> 15:08, 12 August 2019 (UTC)</li>
<li><b>Delete</b> as <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTPROMOTION" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOTPROMOTION">WP:NOTPROMOTION</a>, and no substantial sources found. <a href="/wiki/User:Coolabahapple" title="User:Coolabahapple">Coolabahapple</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Coolabahapple" title="User talk:Coolabahapple">talk</a>) 07:09, 14 August 2019 (UTC)</li></ul>

<p>PRODDED for lacking sources. DePRODed by another editor who added a single source. Apparently no other RIS to be found. Therefore fails <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ARTIST" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ARTIST">WP:ARTIST</a>. <a href="/wiki/User:Mccapra" title="User:Mccapra">Mccapra</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mccapra" title="User talk:Mccapra">talk</a>) 04:53, 12 August 2019 (UTC)
